## 1. Data Flow Overview

PakEscrow's data layer is organized around a **hub-and-spoke dependency model**. The `users` table is the central hub — every other table in the system has at least one foreign key pointing back to it. The `contracts` table is a secondary hub — `payments`, `milestones`, and `disputes` all depend on it.

Data moves through the system in **eight distinct flows**, each triggered by a real-world event (a user signing up, a client depositing funds, a freelancer submitting work, etc.). Each flow writes to one or more tables, reads from dependent tables to validate integrity, and produces outputs in the form of updated balances, status changes, notifications, and audit entries.

```
 EXTERNAL WORLD                     PAKESCROW DATABASE
 ─────────────                      ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
 User fills form  ──WRITE──▶  [ users ]  ──▶  [ wallets ]
                                  │
                  ──WRITE──▶  [ kyc_documents ]
                                  │
 Client creates   ──WRITE──▶  [ contracts ]  ──▶  [ milestones ]
 contract                         │
                                  ├──▶  [ payments ]
                                  │
                                  ├──▶  [ disputes ]
                                  │
 Every action     ──WRITE──▶  [ audit_logs ]
                  ──WRITE──▶  [ notifications ]
                                  │
 Dashboard /      ◀──READ───  All tables
 Reports / APIs
```

